### **Granting TreeViewer permission to open files**

These instructions will guide you through granting TreeViewer permission to open files on your computer. This is optional; however (due to Apple security policies) if you do not complete these steps, you may not be able to open files in TreeViewer by double-clicking them or dragging them on the app's icon.

1. Click on the apple menu and select `System Preferences...`

<p align="center">
    <img height="80" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</p>

2. Open the `Security & Privacy` panel.

<p align="center">
    <img height="150" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</p>

3. Click on the `Privacy` tab.

<p align="center">
    <img height="150" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</p>

4. If the lock at the bottom left is locked, click on it to unlock it so that you can make changes.

<p align="center">
    <img height="300" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</p>

5. Select the `Full Disk Access` category and click on the plus (`+`) button.

<p align="center">
    <img height="300" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</p>

6. Select the `TreeViewer` app and click on `Open`.

<p align="center">
    <img height="300" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</p>

7. The `TreeViewer` app should have been added to the list. Make sure that the check box next to the app name on the left is checked.

<p align="center">
    <img height="300" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</p>

8. Close the System preferences and click on the `Restart` button below to restart TreeViewer.
